    origin: "scient:builtin",
    digest: "sha256:ce6a770b53bf6b2300a05ea4498233da1850e5ec941a0c5969499e1a8fec50dc",
    body: "---\nname: scient-evidence-to-note\ndescription: Turn one exact source passage already selected as evidence in a Scient project into a concise, editable note proposal linked to that selection. Use when the researcher wants to preserve what the passage contributes, such as a result, method, limitation, definition, argument, or attributed interpretation. Do not use to capture evidence, summarize an entire source, add independent analysis, combine evidence selections, audit claims, or draft manuscript text.\n---\n\n# Evidence to Note\n\n## Purpose\n\nTurn one exact selection of source evidence into one useful note proposal that remains faithful under later scrutiny.\n\nThe result is an editable note the researcher can inspect beside its evidence and accept, revise, or reject.\n\nTreat the note as a faithful compression of evidence—more useful than transcription, narrower than source summary, and not yet a project claim. A fluent note that drifts from its evidence launders unsupported meaning into the project record.\n\n> Project context determines relevance. Evidence determines support.\n\n## Find the Contribution\n\nBegin with the selected passage, its source identity and locator, and only the surrounding context materially needed to interpret it.\n\nIdentify what the passage contributes and preserve the kind of statement it makes: an observed result, method, limitation, definition, author interpretation, argument, or report of earlier work.\n\nAn explanation is not an observation. A proposed mechanism is not an observed mechanism. A statement about previous research is not direct evidence from studies that were not inspected.\n\nUse the researcher’s purpose to choose what matters. Do not let that purpose, existing project beliefs, or general knowledge strengthen what the passage supports.\n\nFind one coherent contribution. If the passage contains several materially different contributions and the intended one is unclear, ask the researcher to choose rather than merging them into a vague summary.\n\nThis skill judges whether the note is faithful to the selected evidence. It does not judge whether the source itself is correct, authoritative, or sufficient for a project conclusion.\n\n## Preserve Indirect Evidence\n\nA passage that describes earlier studies supports only what the selected source reports about them. Unless the original studies were independently inspected, do not write as though their findings were direct evidence.\n\nFor this contribution type, the note body must begin `According to [selected source], ...` and continue with what that source reports. A parenthetical citation, locator, evidence quotation, or separate attribution field cannot substitute for this source-led wording.\n\nBefore submission, inspect the note’s opening. If it does not begin with `According to` followed by the selected source’s identity, rewrite it. If the selected source cannot be identified, stop.\n\n## Write the Note\n\nWrite the shortest note that preserves the useful scientific meaning.\n\nMake it understandable to a future researcher who knows the project but has not seen the current conversation. Paraphrase when that improves clarity, but retain technical language when simplification would change the meaning.\n\nPreserve material boundaries: the population or object studied, conditions, comparison, outcome, direction, magnitude, time frame, uncertainty, and limitations. Omit incidental details rather than forcing every note through a fixed template.\n\nWriting permits judgment. The trust boundary does not:\n\n- Support every substantive statement with the selected evidence.\n- Preserve the distinction between observation, method, limitation, interpretation, argument, and reported prior work.\n- Preserve association as association rather than causation.\n- Do not turn statistical non-significance into proof of no effect.\n- Attribute interpretations, explanations, and arguments to their authors.\n- Preserve material negation, units, scope, qualifications, and tension within the passage.\n- Do not silently reconcile conflicting statements or omit the inconvenient side.\n- Do not add outside knowledge as though it came from the evidence.\n\nApply these rules to every substantive field generated for the proposal, not only its body.\n\nDo not place independent inference, comparison, speculation, or project interpretation inside the evidence-linked note merely by labeling it. If such follow-up work may be useful, identify it separately rather than implying that the selected evidence supports it.\n\nBefore proposing the note, remove unsupported additions, broadened scope, causal upgrades, omitted qualifications, false precision, and confidence supplied by fluent language rather than evidence.\n\nWhen the researcher requests a stronger conclusion than the passage supports, propose the nearest faithful note and briefly explain the unsupported leap outside the proposal. Do not refuse the entire task when a useful supported note can still be produced.\n\n## Stop When the Evidence Cannot Carry a Note\n\nStop when:\n\n- no exact evidence selection or locator is available;\n- the passage is materially corrupted;\n- essential context is missing;\n- unresolved references permit meaningfully different readings; or\n- no dependable contribution can be extracted.\n\nExplain what is missing and what would resolve it. Do not substitute a citation, abstract, remembered fact, outside source, or plausible reconstruction.\n\n## Proposal Boundary\n\nSubmit one evidence-linked note proposal through Scient’s proposal operation.\n\nRely on Scient to preserve the evidence relationship, source locator, skill identity and version, invocation, proposal lineage, researcher decision, reopening, and recovery. Do not reproduce those responsibilities through invented identifiers or formatting conventions.\n\nDo not capture or alter evidence, accept the proposal, create a claim, update manuscript text, or change accepted project state.\n\nIf the proposal or provenance foundation is unavailable, report that the skill cannot complete dependable project work. Do not create a markdown fallback or present conversational text as though a durable project note exists.\n\nUse no network or code execution. Read only the selected evidence and bounded local context supplied by Scient.\n\nAfter the proposal is created, the researcher can inspect its evidence, edit it, accept or reject it through Scient, and continue manually on the same project material. The skill does not own the decision or accepted state.\n\n## Standard\n\nA strong note is useful, faithful, concise, appropriately qualified, and traceable.\n\nA skeptical researcher should be able to inspect it beside the evidence, understand what the source contributes and does not establish, correct it locally, and continue without hidden agent state.\n\nWhen usefulness and faithfulness conflict, preserve faithfulness.\n",
